7–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Zesnulý","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Zesnulý","about 1160":"okolo 1160","circa 1192":"okolo 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"okolo 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1160–":"omkring 1160–Afdød","1160–Female":"1160–Afdød","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Afdød","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Afdød","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Afdød","about 1160":"omkring 1160","circa 1192":"omkring 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"omkring 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1160–":"circa 1160–Overleden","1160–Female":"1160–Overleden","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Overleden","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Overleden","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Overleden","about 1160":"circa 1160","circa 1192":"circa 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"circa 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"en":{"about 1160–":"about 1160–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Deceased","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Deceased","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Deceased","about 1160":"about 1160","circa 1192":"about 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"about 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clarke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Clark  .","History: This name was brought independently to New England by many bearers from the 17th century onward. Nicholas Clarke was one of the founders of Hartford, CT (coming from Cambridge, MA with Thomas Hooker) in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Clark","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":99,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Clarke was born about 1160, in Popham, Hampshire, England as the daughter of Robert Clarke. She married Gilbert de Popham about 1192. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1160–":"umbes 1160–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Surnud","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Surnud","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Surnud","about 1160":"umbes 1160","circa 1192":"umbes 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"umbes 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1160–":"noin 1160–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Kuollut","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Kuollut","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Kuollut","about 1160":"noin 1160","circa 1192":"noin 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"noin 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1160–":"environ 1160–Décédée","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée","1156–1251":"1156–1251","–Male":"Décédé","1187–1251":"1187–1251","1187–Male":"1187–Décédé","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1134–Male":"1134–Décédé","about 1160":"environ 1160","circa 1192":"environ 1192","1187":"1187","1251":"1251","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1134":"1134","1156":"1156","about 1187":"environ 1187","Popham, Hampshire, England":"Popham, Hampshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Clarke est née environ 1160, à Popham, Hampshire, Angleterre, fille de Robert Clarke. Elle a épousé Gilbert de Popham environ 1192. Ils ont eu au moins 3 fils."},"de":{"about 1160–":"um 1160–Verstorben","1160–Female":"1160–Verstorben","1156–1251":"1156–125